1 3. A notification or report submitted pursuant to subsection 1
2 must not contain any information that would lead to the
3 identification of any research subject participating in the pilot
4 program.
5 4. A practitioner or entity shall not implement a pilot program
6 unless the practitioner or entity complies with the provisions of this
7 section.
8 5. Nothing in the provisions of this section:
9 (a) Requires the Legislative Counsel Bureau to evaluate, review
10 or take any action other than receiving the notifications and reports
11 pursuant to this section.
12 (b) Prohibits a practitioner or entity from collaborating with an
13 institution of higher education in this State to provide support
14 concerning the pilot program, including, without limitation, training,
15 data collection or ethical review.
16 (c) Prohibits a practitioner or entity or the collaborator of a
17 practitioner or entity, including, without limitation, an institution of
18 higher education in this State with whom the practitioner or entity is
19 collaborating, from accepting gifts, grants, donations and other
20 resources of money to support the pilot program.
21 6. As used in this section:
22 (a) “Electromagnetic brain pulse treatment” means a
23 noninvasive and non-pharmaceutical treatment that uses
24 electroencephalography and transcranial magnetic stimulation to
25 identify abnormal patterns in brainwaves and provide therapeutic
26 electromagnetic stimulation to normalize brain activity.
27 (b) “Pilot program” means a research project that involves the
28 provision of transcranial magnetic stimulation or electromagnetic
29 brain pulse treatment, or both, to subjects in this State.
30 (c) “Transcranial magnetic stimulation” means a noninvasive
31 procedure that uses magnetic pulses to stimulate specific areas of
32 the brain to alter brain activity.
33 Sec. 2. This act becomes effective on October 1, 2025, and
34 expires by limitation on September 30, 2027.
